<span id="freeTextContainer7124396698278466519">“<i>It is a most wonderful comfort to sit alone beneath a lamp, book spread before you, and commune with someone from the past whom you have never met.</i>” <br/><br/>Beautifully written. If I had a pen while reading this book, it would have been a beautiful massacre of underlined sentences, a firework of tiny stars and exclamation marks.<br/><br/>These tiny essay excerptions from a thirteenth-century Japanese monk leaves much food for thought. When reading Kenkō&apos;s praises of boredom, I couldn&apos;t help but wonder how he wou</span>
  <span id="freeText7124396698278466519" style="display:none">“<i>It is a most wonderful comfort to sit alone beneath a lamp, book spread before you, and commune with someone from the past whom you have never met.</i>” <br /><br />Beautifully written. If I had a pen while reading this book, it would have been a beautiful massacre of underlined sentences, a firework of tiny stars and exclamation marks.<br /><br />These tiny essay excerptions from a thirteenth-century Japanese monk leaves much food for thought. When reading Kenkō's praises of boredom, I couldn't help but wonder how he would feel about today's smartphones, stealing away our minutes, filling our pauses. I'm sure he would have much to say about the subject.<br /><br />And that's the thing that impresses me about his writing; it feels so very modern. So many of his arguments and thoughts are applicable to the lives we lead today. I could easily have been fooled into thinking that book was more recently published. <br /><br />“<i>There is nothing finer than to be alone with nothing to distract you.</i>” </span>
