    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3444995137" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3444995137" />
    <a title="Bookish Bethany" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/105715770-bookish-bethany"><img alt="Bookish Bethany" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1626817762p2/105715770.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3444995137?book_show_action=true">Jul 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bookish Bethany" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bookish Bethany" href="/user/show/105715770-bookish-bethany">Bookish Bethany</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3444995137" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18379710710263687626">This was an amusing little book to read, this 13th century monk had a sharp sense of humour. He condemns the drunk, but loves to drink sake until he&apos;s giddy under cherry blossom trees; he talks of women, it seems, only as wives or objects of lust that should be avoided; he says people would be much more tolerable if they lived alone; he hates gossip, yet gossips about the the misconduct of fellow monks and &apos;common folk&apos;. All of this is problematic to say the least (but can we excuse him for bein</span>
  <span id="freeText18379710710263687626" style="display:none">This was an amusing little book to read, this 13th century monk had a sharp sense of humour. He condemns the drunk, but loves to drink sake until he's giddy under cherry blossom trees; he talks of women, it seems, only as wives or objects of lust that should be avoided; he says people would be much more tolerable if they lived alone; he hates gossip, yet gossips about the the misconduct of fellow monks and 'common folk'. All of this is problematic to say the least (but can we excuse him for being 7,000 years old?). <br /><br />Despite all that (and his questionably sexist opinions about women ensnaring men and stripping them of their wit, only to become wizened old hags), there is a lot of wisdom in this. He talks of animal welfare, strong governance, respecting the land, being compassionate towards others, being still but not complacent, speaking before thinking, listening, giving and avoiding a life of excess and greed. <br /><br />It was the passages on excess, greed and the buddist way of living slowly that stuck with me. He tells his audience to not spend our short lives seeking pleasure, wealth, material goods, social status, success or putting others down to get ahead. In our divided world where the wealthy hoard and the poor struggle - this is incredibly needed advice. Rather, Kenko says we should seek connection and enlightenment and embrace a slower way of life. That resonated. <br /><br />Kenko's opinion on life as something to be savoured and cherished is still something we need to remind ourselves of. In many ways he was ahead of his time. <br /><br />We need to stop being greedy and appreciate what we have. We need to realise that 'getting the most out of life' isn't about speed, power, success or money - it's about love, stillness and giving.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18379710710263687626" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

